Description: Wooden fragment of Ramses VI: incised with the Horus name of Ramses VI. This fragment is covered in slight cracks, and there are several large gouges on the surface. There are no traces of colour.
Curator's comments: This fragment probably belonged to a shrine. Bibliography: K. A. Kitchen, 'Ramesside inscriptions : translated & annotated Translations' Vol.7 (Oxford: Blackwell Press), p359 B. Porter & R. Moss, 'Topographical Bibliography of Ancient Egyptian Hieroglyphic Texts, Reliefs and Paintings' III (2) (Oxford: Clarendon Press), 824
Bibliographic references: Insley Green 1987 / The temple furniture from the sacred animal necropolis at North Saqqara, 1964-1976 (7)
Bierbrier 1993 / Hieroglyphic texts from Egyptian stelae, etc., in the British Museum, Part 12. (Pl.14-15)
Condition: Preservation and colour: This fragment is covered in slight cracks, and there are several large gouges on the surface. There are no traces of colour.
